- This commit chooses the optimal vector size that is compatible with
  the data shape and pointer alignment.

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.
- Some quick benchmarking showed the following speedups with this commit
  when gathering vectors of length 256 on an NVIDIA TITAN V GPU:

  the data shape and pointer alignment.

  vectorized types, but it is not actually needed: the use of 'const
  __restrict__' means the kernel still generates LDG instructions
  without it.

These were needed when attempting to use the output folder from the
project generation (with OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis_nn and
TARGET=cortex_m_generic) to build binaries for the SParkfun Edge.

We do not have any CI that would catch such regressions. The issue at
hand is that with large external libraries (such as CMSIS), it can
becomes complex to figure out exactly what all the headers are.

This issue of managing third_party dependencies is more general that
project generation so we are currently ok with not having CI coverage
for the CMSIS as part of project generation.

In fact, in the case of the Sparkfun Edge, the Ambiq SDK packages its
own version of (a small subset of) CMSIS headers. It is possible that
folks might want to consolidate such third party dependencies and
maintain their own version of CMSIS instead of relying on the headers /
sources that are exported by the TFLM project generation scripts.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rd16395p/tensorflow/commits/c2611f80f925fda5db47b0e225510821c885a649"},{"sha":"0341acc930873b183cd5f002d148a46997f4736f","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] [NFC] CollectiveScheduleLinearizer: test for dependent collectives

PiperOrigin-RevId: 361234109
Change-Id: I5a89b41f600d6e03c75366fb41e1b5fdbefe9f1a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rd16395p/tensorflow/commits/de5bfc8bb62ee0b73f0d84e9f7f37b83475f4371"},{"sha":"0029a3c377e9e0e05d6a381dda1ac418f4357e9f","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Fix bug when LossScaleOptimizer and gradient_aggregator were used.

Before, if there were multiple processes each with a LossScaleOptimizer, and the inner optimizer had a custom gradient_aggregator to aggregate gradients across the processes, the LossScaleOptimizers in the processes could become out of sync. In particular, if a strict subset of replicas encountered NaN gradients, only the LossScaleOptimizers with NaN gradients would skip the step, while the LossScaleOptimizers with finite gradients would still apply gradients

Resolves https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46863. Horovod was broken with LossScaleOptimizer in TF 2.4 due to this bug, but they patched in a workaround. With this fix, the workaround will not be necessary in TF 2.5.

The issue was caused by the fact the gradients were checked for NaNs before they were all-reduced. This was handled correctly with tf.distribute.Strategy but not with an arbitrary gradient_aggregator. Now, the gradients are all-reduced before they are checked for NaNs, which means if any replica has NaNs, they all will have NaNs.

This potentially will allow better performance in the future as well, as it allows earlier-computed gradients to be all-reduced in parallel with the computation of later-computed gradients.

[{"sha":"dfb9832a25e8d1852e158bbcead941d3a5941343","author":{"name":"Alexander Alekhin","email":"68add3c7f0912f500ebe6e9539930fd1bb229c72@gmail.com"},"message":"cmake(protobuf): ensure using of own headers","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tahoma2d/opencv/commits/dfb9832a25e8d1852e158bbcead941d3a5941343"},{"sha":"da555a2c9bdce45a944ff4c85a2981b79d763724","author":{"name":"Clement Courbet","email":"18a6ad33eeb00c3a39b33c2572bde72aa7e82ab1@google.com"},"message":"Optimize opencv dft by vectorizing radix2 and radix3.

This is useful for non power-of-two sizes when WITH_IPP is not an option.

This shows consistent improvement over openCV benchmarks, and we measure
even larger improvements on our internal workloads.

For example, for 320x480, `32FC*`, we can see a ~5% improvement}, as
`320=2^6*5` and `480=2^5*3*5`, so the improved radix3 version is used.
`64FC*` is flat as expected, as we do not specialize the functors for `double`
in this change.
